<!-- ── FORMULA ── -->
<section class="content-section reveal">
  <h2>The Formula</h2>
  <p>UK mortgage repayments are calculated using the <strong>annuity formula</strong>, which gives you a fixed monthly payment covering both interest and capital repayment over the term.</p>
  <div class="formula-box">
    M = P [ r(1 + r)<sup>n</sup> ] / [ (1 + r)<sup>n</sup> &minus; 1 ]<br><br>
    Where:<br>
    M = monthly repayment<br>
    P = principal (loan amount)<br>
    r = monthly interest rate (annual rate &divide; 12)<br>
    n = total number of monthly payments (term in years &times; 12)
  </div>

  <h3>Income multiplier</h3>
  <p>Most UK lenders use an <strong>income multiplier</strong> to determine how much you can borrow. The standard multiplier is 4.5 times your gross annual income, though some lenders offer up to 5.5&times; for higher earners.</p>
  <div class="formula-box">
    Maximum Borrowing = Gross Annual Income &times; 4.5
  </div>
</section>

